WEBVTT

00:08.820 --> 00:12.780
Coming up next is the Science Fiction Radio Show, so stay with us.

00:28.820 --> 00:34.240
This is the Science Fiction Radio Show, a commentary on science fiction and fantasy.

00:37.180 --> 00:38.680
And here are your hosts.

00:43.500 --> 00:45.680
This is Daryl Lane and Bill Vernon.

00:46.180 --> 00:49.220
Today we're beginning a three part series on science fiction author Lee Killow.

00:49.620 --> 00:54.580
Killow is a Kansas native who wrote several short stories during the 1970s, then produced

00:54.580 --> 00:57.120
four novels in short order in the 1980s.

00:57.460 --> 01:02.080
She began as a writer of hard science fiction, but here we find out how she converted to

01:02.080 --> 01:03.980
the more character oriented variety.

01:05.100 --> 01:09.140
I started out and my interest was mostly in really hard science fiction.

01:09.280 --> 01:11.320
I was a die hard analog reader.

01:13.400 --> 01:18.080
And the first story I ever sold was to analog and it was an analog kind of story.

01:19.600 --> 01:22.280
I haven't sold a story to analog since.

01:22.500 --> 01:27.760
Almost everything I've written since has come out in, the majority of it has come out

01:27.760 --> 01:28.780
in the fantasy science fiction.

01:28.940 --> 01:33.740
I've had one in Galileo and a couple in GIF Magazine before it folded.

01:35.200 --> 01:40.380
But I got more and more interested in people and realizing that hardware wasn't the thing,

01:40.640 --> 01:44.520
that it was people and that people were interesting and what made them tick.

01:45.640 --> 01:53.060
And so the more I started researching that, the more I got interested in what makes society

01:53.060 --> 01:53.620
to click.

01:53.620 --> 01:59.100
And then when I started making up aliens and I started reading a lot of anthropology to

01:59.100 --> 02:04.660
figure out, you know, really how societies go together, the more I read, the more I researched,

02:04.820 --> 02:06.060
the more fascinated I got.

02:07.460 --> 02:10.480
Kilo goes to great lengths to keep the details of her books consistent.

02:11.100 --> 02:14.060
Listeners she explains how she is able to keep track of the minutiae.

02:15.120 --> 02:19.800
I put together a background book before I ever start the novel itself.

02:19.800 --> 02:25.740
It's an amount of work that I know some people find exhausting.

02:26.720 --> 02:30.000
They couldn't do it and still have any energy left to write the book.

02:30.540 --> 02:32.920
But I enjoy it.

02:33.020 --> 02:33.840
I'm very systematic.

02:35.760 --> 02:38.620
I start out with a lot of visual images in my head.

02:39.260 --> 02:46.900
And with vague visual images, you have to have them developed to a very clear image

02:47.520 --> 02:51.840
and you have to find the words for them and get them translated into actual words out

02:51.840 --> 02:53.760
of pictures before you can get them down on paper.

02:54.940 --> 02:58.900
So I do a background book and I do maps of the planet.

02:59.140 --> 03:04.460
I do drawings of the flora and fauna and biogas and these are the people.

03:05.480 --> 03:13.280
And the more I read and read on climatology and planetology, the more complex backgrounds

03:13.280 --> 03:13.620
get.

03:13.960 --> 03:20.600
It takes me about the same amount of time to put a background together but it gets much

03:20.600 --> 03:21.300
more complicated.

03:21.460 --> 03:22.860
Now they're almost finished.

03:23.200 --> 03:25.960
Background is almost as thick as the final manuscript on the book.

03:27.180 --> 03:29.900
Writers have many reasons for applying their trade.

03:30.440 --> 03:35.020
Kelo has an interesting point of view on the role and rewards of writers including herself.

03:36.180 --> 03:38.780
A writer entertains.

03:38.780 --> 03:45.320
And if he thinks that he's creating desolate prose with every line he struggles to put down

03:45.320 --> 03:53.220
and if he's writing for history, then he's probably got pretensions of grandeur.

03:54.820 --> 04:02.620
If I write a book that people buy and read by buying, they give me my money which I need.

04:02.620 --> 04:07.060
And if they enjoy it by reading it, then I'm really happy.

04:08.940 --> 04:15.700
I don't think I would write a book just for money but certainly I want to write something

04:15.700 --> 04:20.000
that is fun for me to write and I want to write something that is fun for readers to read.

04:21.740 --> 04:25.300
Kelo's work sell demand with all's well and they lived happily ever after.

04:25.780 --> 04:27.640
She believes that life is fraught with problems.

04:29.040 --> 04:35.420
There are a lot of large social problems that exist within each book that never get solved.

04:36.100 --> 04:39.640
But people in the book solve their own problems.

04:39.840 --> 04:41.040
They handle their own lives.

04:41.500 --> 04:45.600
And I think maybe that a little bit of personal philosophy of mine comes through that.

04:46.180 --> 04:50.500
I can't solve the world's problems but I can certainly keep control of my own life.

04:51.060 --> 04:54.020
And my belief in that I can pass on.

