18:25.480 --> 18:31.080
He burst under the science fiction scene in 1981 with one of the most original novels to appear in years, White Light.

18:31.980 --> 18:34.540
But White Light was not the first novel Rucker authored.

19:02.040 --> 19:05.860
I wrote this. I wrote it during summer, not teaching in New York.

19:08.920 --> 19:17.020
And there what I wanted to do with that book was make a strong anarchist statement about the way I felt in that society.

19:17.720 --> 19:24.940
It was, you know, like basically sort of late 60s, really, even though it was really big 70s.

19:25.700 --> 19:28.680
Rucker was unable to sell space-time donuts immediately.

19:29.220 --> 19:32.400
Here he tells us a story behind his very successful White Light.

19:33.260 --> 19:35.860
The way I came to write White Light was kind of weird.

19:37.960 --> 19:41.080
I wrote space-time donuts and I couldn't sell them anywhere.

19:41.880 --> 19:45.260
And finally, on Earth Magazine agreed to serialize it.

19:45.940 --> 19:51.520
And they serialized the first two parts of it and they went out of business.

19:52.980 --> 19:57.480
And at that point I lost my job when I was teaching in New York.

19:58.320 --> 20:00.140
They would give me 10 years of time.

20:01.340 --> 20:06.680
But then I got a grant to go to do mathematics in Germany.

20:07.820 --> 20:09.900
And I got a grant from the German government.

20:10.700 --> 20:14.500
Went to Heidelberg. Went there for, I had a two-year, well, a two-year grant there.

20:16.040 --> 20:18.180
And it's from the Fund Homeboat Foundation.

20:18.180 --> 20:21.160
That's why some of my books are dedicated to Homeboat.

20:23.720 --> 20:29.660
And I got over there and to my delight I discovered that the person in charge of my research

20:29.660 --> 20:31.560
really didn't care about mathematics either.

20:32.300 --> 20:34.080
So I just started writing science fiction.

20:35.980 --> 20:40.420
And I spent about three months trying to solve this problem, continuum problem.

20:41.160 --> 20:44.400
Like that, you know, I knew a lot about it. It's a very difficult problem.

20:45.360 --> 20:47.940
And then I said, well, I'm just going to write a novel about it.

20:48.240 --> 20:50.300
And then I came to write White Light that way.

20:50.540 --> 20:52.460
Which, it's about different levels of affinity.

20:54.080 --> 20:57.720
The packaging of an American edition of White Light made it appear as though the book

20:57.720 --> 21:00.100
were another in a long line of life after life books.

21:00.740 --> 21:02.200
We asked Rucker how this came about.

21:03.780 --> 21:06.800
Well, that was Jim Bain. He was the editor of Ace at that time.

21:07.380 --> 21:10.560
And he bought it. I was happy that he bought it.

21:10.740 --> 21:11.680
You know, he gave me good money.

21:11.680 --> 21:14.820
It was his marketing decision.

21:15.080 --> 21:20.840
He probably thought, well, we can film more copies if we package it as something for

21:22.860 --> 21:27.360
superstitious foolish people instead of packaging it as avant-garde literature.

21:28.600 --> 21:30.300
I imagine he's probably right.

21:31.300 --> 21:33.920
We asked Rucker if he had any input on the packaging.

21:35.000 --> 21:38.240
Well, the one thing I got him to put on the cover was, do you want to see God?

21:38.240 --> 21:41.120
I got him to put that on the back.

21:42.340 --> 21:46.100
We asked Rucker how people who bought the book thinking it was a straight life after life

21:46.100 --> 21:47.560
novel reacted to it.

21:48.520 --> 21:53.520
Well, I've met people since then that are really into like dream stuff and after travel.

21:54.040 --> 21:58.800
Like, they've read it and very seriously and they're just like, don't understand why

21:58.800 --> 22:02.440
the book is sort of not so serious as it should be.

