The young guy who's sort of, you know, based on a guy that I used to hang around with,

24:56.540 --> 25:02.240
a guy younger than me, and the old guy in there is, can extend based on their father.

25:04.080 --> 25:07.760
In Software, a simulacrum of the famous mathematician Girdle,

25:08.120 --> 25:11.200
makes a brief appearance to lecture on Girdle's incompleteness theorem.

25:11.800 --> 25:15.400
This theorem says that humans cannot build robots as intelligent as themselves.

25:16.000 --> 25:19.240
Rucker had several discussions with Girdle shortly before Girdle died.

25:19.240 --> 25:21.360
Listen as he describes the relationship.

25:51.460 --> 25:54.040
I'll think about Girdle when you talk to him.

25:54.100 --> 25:56.160
When I talk to him, I go and make up a list of questions.

25:56.360 --> 26:01.800
I want to ask him about all this stuff, about math and philosophy and physics and so on.

26:02.460 --> 26:07.660
And I keep it sitting alone in Princeton there, like for 30 years.

26:07.980 --> 26:12.080
Like 30 years ago, he approved the heaviest things that anybody had ever done in mathematics.

26:13.020 --> 26:17.120
He'd been like 30 years past that. He was thinking all the time.

26:17.500 --> 26:21.360
And anything I'd ask him, you know, like he'd already been all the way down the road.

26:22.420 --> 26:27.000
And he would just laugh. I mean, a lot of when I talk to him, he'd say a few words and then he'd start laughing.

26:27.660 --> 26:28.820
And I'd start laughing with him.

26:30.100 --> 26:33.980
And like as we would laugh, I would feel like we were communicating.

26:34.480 --> 26:39.040
It was awesome. I mean, it sounds kind of stupid when I say it like this, but awesome.

26:39.620 --> 26:42.000
It was, you know, like a real feeling of telepathy almost.

26:42.000 --> 26:45.200
Like, you know, just anything I'd say you'd totally understand.

26:46.020 --> 26:50.520
Which is really unquestionably the greatest person I've ever made.

26:52.800 --> 26:56.380
The German philosopher Hegel is Rucker several times removed Grandfather.

26:56.940 --> 26:59.980
We asked him if there is any of Hegel's influence in his work.

27:01.300 --> 27:04.380
I think I've done my part, you know, for the absolute.

27:05.420 --> 27:09.300
I really, I'd like to read his stuff and it's pretty hard to read.

27:09.840 --> 27:13.240
I've read books about him, but the actual books are very hard to read.

27:13.860 --> 27:23.840
But it's my impression that I have somewhat the same ideas about the absolute, the absolute being the ultimate thing, the white life.

27:25.760 --> 27:34.700
And I would say, you know, like later people look back and say, well, it's pretty much what Hegel would have wanted to write if he was a scientist.

27:37.600 --> 27:42.500
Rudy Rucker, the science fiction author who plans to continue doing his part for the absolute.

28:24.080 --> 28:25.480
I'm not sure what I'm saying.

